      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "When a cold front hits, people usually see a rapid line of towering cumulonimbus clouds that often bring heavy rain, thunderstorms, or even hail. It happens very quickly; the front can move at speeds of 20 to 40 miles per hour, so the weather changes from sunny to stormy in a matter of hours. Once the front passes, the skies usually clear up within a day or two, and the wind shifts to a cooler direction as the cold air mass takes over.\n\nThis sudden transition is quite dramatic, often described as a \"wall of weather\" that sweeps across the landscape. The speed of the front means there isn't much time to prepare, which is why people often get caught off guard by the intense precipitation and strong gusts.\n\nTo visualize the speed, imagine a convoy of fast-moving trucks carrying storm clouds; they don't stop, and the weather inside the convoy is intense. The gap between the warm air ahead and the cold air behind is narrow, so the interaction is brief but powerful.\n\nIn summary, you typically see heavy storms and dark clouds right as the front arrives, followed by clearing skies and cooler temperatures. The process is fast and intense, leaving a lasting mark on the local",
